    {
      "id": "grat_analysis",
      "title": "GRAT Analysis",
      "content_type": "narrative",
      "purpose": "Present the full mechanics of a Grantor Retained Annuity Trust for this client. Define what a GRAT is, how it is funded, and how it freezes the transferred value for transfer-tax purposes. Explain the §7520 hurdle-rate mechanism and compute the spread between assumed growth and the hurdle. Describe the annuity payment structure, including the zeroed-out design and the fact that the taxable gift equals only the remainder interest. Cover grantor-trust income-tax treatment under IRC §671. Provide a thorough mortality-risk analysis tied to the client's age and the chosen term, including comparison with shorter rolling GRATs and longer terms. Note that annuity payments may increase by up to 20% annually under regulations. Discuss what happens if returns fail to exceed the hurdle rate. Address the irrevocable nature of the transfer and administrative complexity.",
