    {
      "id": "crat_analysis",
      "title": "CRAT Analysis",
      "content_type": "narrative",
      "purpose": "Present the full mechanics of a Charitable Remainder Annuity Trust for this client. Define a CRAT as a trust paying a fixed annuity to one or more noncharitable beneficiaries with the remainder passing to charity, and explain how it is funded. State clearly that the annuity is fixed at inception based on the initial fair market value and does not change with trust performance. Explain both lifetime and term-of-years structures, including the 20-year maximum for term-of-years under 26 CFR §1.664-2. Cover the 10% charitable remainder minimum and whether this client's trust clears the threshold. Explain the four-tier taxation of distributions under IRC §664. Explain estate-tax treatment under IRC §2036 and the offsetting charitable deduction. Explain that the charitable deduction represents the present value of the charity's remainder interest. Compare the CRAT's performance dependence (payout rate) with the GRAT's (§7520 rate). Note the absence of a mortality-risk penalty equivalent to the GRAT. Discuss the irrevocable nature of the transfer, administrative complexity, and whether a wealth-replacement strategy for heirs should be considered.",
